Put all but 2 tbsp of your @wholemeal flour{150%g} into a #high sided bowl{} with @salt{1/4%tsp}. Very gradually add @water{about 1/3%cup} into the flour whilst you mix it with your hands. Keep mixing and adding until you have a soft (not soggy!) dough.

Sprinkle the remaining flour onto your work surface and coat the dough in @olive oil{1%tsp}. Knead the dough by pushing it away from you on the work surface. Form it back into a ball and then push it away again to stretch it. Once you've pummelled it for a few mins leave it to rest.

Chop the @aubergine{2} into (roughly) 2cm cubes. Peel the @onion{1} and cut in half through the root. Cut each half into slices widthways to get half moon shapes. Peel and finely dice the @garlic{2%cloves} and roughly chop the @coriander{1/2}(roughly chopped).

Heat a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Toss the aubergine in @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Fry off the aubergine cubes until golden brown (around ~{8%minutes}).

Add the onion slices and the garlic to the #pan{} and cook for ~{5%minutes}, or until soft. Add the @mild chili powder{1/2%tsp}, @ground coriander{1%tsp}, @ground cumin{1%tsp} and @turmeric{1} and mix well, then chop (don't peel) your @potato{1} into 2 cm cubes. Add @vegetable stock pot{1/2} to the pan with @water{200%ml} and stir until it dissolves. Add in the potato cubes, cover with a #lid{} and cook for ~{10%minutes}.

Remove the lid and let the sauce bubble until it has reduced by a third. Add @baby spinach{1%large handful} (wash the leaves first if they need it). Stir well to combine everything and simmer for ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove from the heat and after a couple of mins stir through a few tbsps of @Greek style yoghurt{3%tbsp}.

Finally, roll out your chapatis with a #rolling pin{} until they are as thin as a pancake. If you don't have a rolling pin you can use a #wine bottle{} or even a #tin can{}! Place them in a searing hot frying pan and cook on both sides until you see little light brown spots form.

== Raita ==

Mix @Greek style yoghurt{3%tbsp} with @coriander{1%tsp}(chopped), @salt{1/4%tsp} and @pepper{a few grinds} to make a 'raita' (AKA yoghurt sauce).

== To Serve ==

Serve the curry with the chapatis and sprinkle over the remaining coriander, the raita and the @flaked almonds{1}.